<refentry xml:id="hack.vectortv.construct" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
 <refnamediv>
  <refname>Vector&lt;Tv&gt;::__construct</refname>
  <refpurpose>Creates a Vector</refpurpose>
 </refnamediv>

 <refsect1 role="description">
  &reftitle.description;
  <constructorsynopsis>
   <modifier>public</modifier>
   <methodname>Vector&lt;Tv&gt;::__construct</methodname>
   <methodparam><type>?Traversable&lt;Tv&gt;</type><parameter>it</parameter></methodparam>
  </constructorsynopsis>

<!-- Note: If this method/property as an alternate procedural mapping then the method/property synopsis MUST be listed BEFORE the function synopsis -->
  <para>
   Creates an empty Vector (if no parameters are passed) or creates a Vector from a Traversable.
  </para>
  <para>
    There are three primary ways to construct a <literal>Vector</literal>:
    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem><simpara><literal>$v = Vector {}; // empty</literal></simpara></listitem>
      <listitem><simpara><literal>$v = Vector {1, 2}; // <link linkend="hack.collections.literalsyntax">literal syntax</link></literal></simpara></listitem>
      <listitem><simpara><literal>$v = new Vector($traversable); // from a <link linkend="hack.collections.interfaces">Traversable</link></literal></simpara></listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </para>
  <para>
    Here is an example of constructing an <literal>Vector</literal> using an <literal>array</literal>
    <informalexample>
      <programlisting role="php" location="hack.vectortv.construct1.php" />
      &example.outputs;
      <screen>
<![CDATA[
object(HH\Vector)#1 (3) {
  [0]=>
  string(1) "a"
  [1]=>
  string(1) "b"
  [2]=>
  string(1) "c"
}
]]>
      </screen>
    </informalexample>
  </para>
 </refsect1>
</refentry>
